1. Install Git
Ensure Git is installed on your system. You can check by running:

sh
Copy
Edit
git --version
If Git is not installed, download and install it from git-scm.com.

2. Configure Git (First-Time Setup)
Set your username and email:

sh
Copy
Edit
git config --global user.name "Your Name"
git config --global user.email "your.email@example.com"
3. Create a New Local Repository
Navigate to your project folder or create a new one:

sh
Copy
Edit
mkdir my-project
cd my-project
Then initialize the repository:

sh
Copy
Edit
git init
This creates a .git directory inside your project, marking it as a Git repository.

4. Add Files to the Repository
Add files to be tracked by Git:

sh
Copy
Edit
git add .
This stages all changes for commit.

5. Commit Changes
Save the changes to the repository:

sh
Copy
Edit
git commit -m "Initial commit"
6. Create a Remote Repository on GitHub (or GitLab, Bitbucket, etc.)
Go to GitHub and create a new repository.
Copy the repository URL.
7. Link Local Repository to Remote
Add the remote repository URL:

sh
Copy
Edit
git remote add origin https://github.com/your-username/your-repo.git
Verify the remote:

sh
Copy
Edit
git remote -v
8. Push Your Code to GitHub
Upload your local commits to the remote repository:

sh
Copy
Edit
git push -u origin main
If using master instead of main, use:

sh
Copy
Edit
git push -u origin master
9. Clone an Existing Repository (Optional)
If you want to clone an existing repository, use:

sh
Copy
Edit
git clone https://github.com/username/repository.git
